# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: national-fire-protection-association
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-institute-of-constructors] The **American Institute of Constructors** (**AIC**), is a not-for-profit 501(c)(6) non-governmental professional association founded in 1971.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-institute-of-constructors] Individuals involved in the AIC are typically found in the construction management Industry.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-institute-of-constructors] The AIC offers three different levels of certification: Associate Constructor (AC), Certified Professional Constructor (CPC), and Fellow (FC).
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-institute-of-constructors] American Institute of Constructors also offers a number of educational programs, including online courses, webinars, and in-person seminars.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The **American Society of Civil Engineers** (**ASCE**) is a tax-exempt professional body founded in 1852 to represent members of the civil engineering profession worldwide.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Headquartered in Reston, Virginia, it is the oldest national engineering society in the United States.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Its constitution was based on the older Boston Society of Civil Engineers from 1848.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] ASCE is dedicated to the advancement of the science and profession of civil engineering and the enhancement of human welfare through the activities of society members.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] It has more than 143,000 members in 177 countries.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Its mission is to provide essential value to members, their careers, partners, and the public; facilitate the advancement of technology; encourage and provide the tools for lifelong learning; promote professionalism and the profession; develop and support civil engineers.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The first serious and documented attempts to organize civil engineers as a professional society in the newly created United States were in the early 19th century.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Later, in 1834, an American trade periodical, the "American Railroad Journal," advocated for a similar national organization of civil engineers.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] On December 17, 1838, a petition started circulating asking civil engineers to meet in 1839 in Baltimore, Maryland, to organize a permanent society of civil engineers.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Prior to that, thirteen notable civil engineers largely identifiable as being from New York, Pennsylvania, or Maryland met in Philadelphia.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Forty engineers actually appeared at the February 1839 meeting in Baltimore, including J.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Edgar Thomson (Future Chief Engineer and later President of the Pennsylvania Railroad), Wright, Roberts, Edward Miller, and the Maryland engineers Isaac Trimble and Benjamin Henry Latrobe II and attendees from as far as Massachusetts, Illinois, and Louisiana.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Miller later ascribed the failure to the difficulties of assembling members due to available means for traveling in the country at the time.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] That journal continued discussion on forming an engineers' organization from 1839 thru 1843 serving its own self-interests in advocating its journal as a replacement for a professional society but to no avail.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] During the 1840s, professional organizations continued to develop and organize in the United States.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] During this same period of association incorporations in the 1840s, attempts were again made at organizing an American engineer association.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] They succeeded at first with the Boston Society of Civil Engineers, organized in 1848, and then in October 1852, with an effort to organize a Society of Civil Engineers and Architects in New York.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Craven, Chief Engineer of the Croton Aqueduct and future ASCE president, the meeting resolved to incorporate the society under the name "American Society of Civil Engineers And Architects".
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The founding meeting was held on November 5, 1852, in the offices of the Croton Aqueduct Department at the Rotunda in City Hall Park, Manhattan.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Membership eligibility was restricted to "civil, geological, mining and mechanical Engineers, architects, and other persons who, by profession, are interested in the advancement of science." James Laurie was elected the society's first president.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] At an early meeting of the Board of Direction in 1852, instructions were given for the incorporation of the "American Society of Civil Engineers and Architects" but this was the proper steps were never taken, and therefore this name never legally belonged to the association.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The ASCE held its first meetings at the Croton Aqueduct Department building in City Hall Park.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The meetings only went through 1855 and with the advent of the American Civil War, the society suspended its activities.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The next meeting was more than twelve years later in 1867.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] A number of the original founders, such as James Laurie, J.W.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Talcott, were at this meeting and were dedicated to the objective of resuscitating the society.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] They also planned to put the society on a more permanent footing and elect fifty-four new members.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] With success in that effort, the young engineering society passed a resolution noting that its preservation was mainly due to the persevering efforts of its first president, James Laurie.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The address of President James Pugh Kirkwood delivered at that meeting in 1867 was the first publication of the society, appearing in Volume 1 of *Transactions*, bearing date of 1872.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] On March 4, 1868, by a vote of 17 to 4, the name was changed to "American Society of Civil Engineers", but it was not until April 17, 1877, that the lack of incorporation was discovered and the proper steps taken to remedy the defect.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The society was then chartered and incorporated in New York state.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The reconvened ASCE met at the Chamber of Commerce of the State of New York until 1875 when the society moved to 4 East 23rd Street.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The ASCE moved again in 1877 to 104 East 20th Street and in 1881 to 127 East 23rd Street.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The ASCE commissioned a new headquarters at 220 West 57th Street in 1895.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The building was completed in 1897 and served as the society's headquarters until 1917 when the ASCE moved to the Engineering Societies' Building.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Nora Stanton Barney was among the first women in the United States to earn a civil engineering degree, graduating from Cornell University in 1905.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] In the same year, she was accepted as a junior member of the organization and began work for the New York City Board of Water Supply.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] She was the first female member of ASCE, where she was allowed to be a junior member, but was denied advancement to associate member in 1916 because of her gender.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] In 2015, she was posthumously advanced to ASCE Fellow status.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] ASCE's headquarters relocated to the Engineering Societies' Building in 1917; additional floors were added on top of the building to accommodate the society's new offices.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The weight of the extra stories could not be supported on the existing pilings, so four new steel columns were constructed through the structure, supported directly on the bedrock.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] In 1961, ASCE's headquarters moved from the Engineering Societies' Building to the United Engineering Center, a new skyscraper built for twenty different engineering societies across from the headquarters of the United Nations.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] In 1996, ASCE relocated its headquarters from New York City to Reston, Virginia.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The relocation to the Washington metropolitan area was made to bring ASCE's headquarters closer to the legislative branch of the federal government and also reduced operating costs.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] In 1999, the ASCE elected the top-ten "civil engineering achievements that had the greatest positive impact on life in the 20th century" in "broad categories".
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Monuments of the Millennium were a "combination of technical engineering achievement, courage and inspiration, and a dramatic influence on the development of [their] communities".
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] ASCE stated that dissemination of technical and professional information to the civil engineering profession was a major goal of the society.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] They also publish an online bibliographic database, conference proceedings, standards, manuals of practice, and technical reports.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The ASCE Library contains 470+ e-books and standards, some with chapter-level access and no restrictive DRM, and 600+ online proceedings.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Each year, more than 55,000 engineers earn continuing education units (CEUs) and/or professional development hours (PDHs) by participating in ASCE's continuing education programs.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] ASCE hosts more than 15 annual and specialty conferences, over 200 continuing education seminars and more than 300 live web seminars.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Meetings include "...committees, task forces, focus groups, workshops and seminars designed to bring together civil engineering experts either from specific fields or those with a broad range of experience and skills.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The engineering programs division directly advances the science of engineering by delivering technical content for ASCE's publications, conferences and continuing education programs.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] It consists of eight discipline-specific institutes, four technical divisions, and six technical councils.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The work is accomplished by over 600 technical committees with editorial responsibility for 28 of ASCE's 33 journals.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] On an annual basis, the division conducts more than twelve congresses and specialty conferences.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] As a founding society of ANSI and accredited standards development organization, ASCE committees use an established and audited process to produce consensus standards under a program supervised by the society's Codes and Standards Committee.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] (CEC), affiliated with ASCE, has been established to support specialty certification academies for civil engineering specialties and is accredited by the Council of Engineering and Scientific Specialty Boards (CESB).
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] CEC also handles safety certification for state, municipal, and federal buildings, formerly the province of the now-defunct Building Security Council.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The Committee on Critical Infrastructure (CCI) provides vision and guidance on ASCE activities related to critical infrastructure resilience, including planning, design, construction, O&M, and event mitigation, response and recovery.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Certification is the recognition of attaining advanced knowledge and skills in a specialty area of civil engineering.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] ASCE offers certifications for engineers who demonstrate advanced knowledge and skills in their area of engineering.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Michel Award for Industry Advancement of Research and the Charles Pankow Award for innovation, 12 scholarships and fellowships for student members.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Created in 1968 by ASCE's Sanitary Engineering Division, the Wesley W.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Horner award is named after former ASCE President Wesley W.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Horner, and given to a recently peer reviewed published paper in the fields of hydrology, urban drainage, or sewerage.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Special consideration is given to private practice engineering work that is recognized as a valuable contribution to the field of environmental engineering.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The Lifetime Achievement Award has been presented annually since 1999 and recognizes five different individual leaders.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] One award is present in each category of design, construction, government, education, and management.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] In July 1946, the Board of Direction authorized annual awards on recommendation by the society's Committee on Research to stimulate research in civil engineering.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Alberta Reed Huber endowed these prizes in honor of her husband, Walter L.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The Huber Prize is considered the highest level mid-career research prize in civil engineering and is awarded for outstanding achievements and contributions in research with respect to all disciplines of civil engineering.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The LTPP International Data Analysis Contest is an annual data analysis contest held by the ASCE in collaboration with the Federal Highway Administration (FHWA).
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The participants utilize Long-Term Pavement Performance Program (LTPP) data as part of their analysis.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] At the instigation of the former students of Nathan Mortimore Newmark, the Nathan M.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Newmark Medal was established in 1975 by the Engineering Mechanics Institute and Structural Engineering Institute of the American Society of Civil Engineers (ASCE) in honor of his contributions in structural engineering and mechanics.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The medal is given to an ASCE member whose outstanding contributions in structural mechanics have substantially strengthened the scientific base of structural engineering, documented in the form of papers or other written presentations.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Nominations are made once a year and due on November 1.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The foundation board of directors has seven persons and its bylaws require that four of the seven directors must be ASCE officers as well and the ASCE executive director and chief financial officer must also be ASCE employees.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The foundation's support is most often to ASCE's charitable, educational and scientific programs.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The foundation's largest program is supporting three strategic areas; lifelong learning and leadership, advocacy for infrastructure investment and the role of civil engineers in sustainable practices.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] In 2014, this foundation's support in these areas was almost US$4 million.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] ASCE provides peer reviews at the request of public agencies and projects as a "means to improve the management and quality of [public agency] services and thus better protect the public health and safety with which they are entrusted".
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] After the 2005 levee failures in Greater New Orleans, the commander of the U.S.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Lawrence Roth, deputy executive director of the ASCE led the ERP development, served as the panel's chief of staff and facilitated its interaction with IPET.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The expert panel's role was to provide an independent technical review of the IPET's activities and findings, as stated at a National Research Council meeting in New Orleans: "an independent review panel ensure[s] that the outcome is a robust, credible and defensible performance evaluation".
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Gen Strock gave all expert review panel members an Outstanding Civilian Service Medals.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] On June 1, 2007, the ASCE issued its expert review panel report, and an accompanying press release.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The corps acknowledged receiving a copy of the letter and refused to comment until the ASCE's Committee on Professional Conduct (CPC) had commented on the complaint.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] It took over a year for the ASCE to announce the results of the CPC.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] On November 14, 2007, ASCE announced that U.S.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] (ret), would lead an independent task force of outside experts to review how ASCE participated in engineering studies of national significance.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] ASCE President David Mongan said the review was to address criticism of ASCE´s role in assisting the Army Corps of Engineers-sponsored investigation of Katrina failures.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Mongan assured citizens of metro New Orleans in a letter to the *Times Picayune*, that ASCE took "this matter very seriously and that appropriate actions are being taken".
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The panel recommended in results released on September 12, 2008, that ASCE should immediately take steps to remove the potential for conflict of interest in its participation in post-disaster engineering studies.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] It concluded that ASCE should draw up an ethics policy to eliminate questions of possible conflicts of interest.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] On April 6, 2009, an internal probe with the ASCE issued a report that ordered a retraction of the ASCE's June 1, 2007, press release.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] On November 5, 2007, New Orleans–based grassroots group *Levees.org* led by Sandy Rosenthal criticized the ASCE's close relationship with the United States Army Corps of Engineers in a spoof online public service announcement.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] On November 12, 2007, the ASCE asked Levees.org to remove the video from the internet, threatening the organization with legal action if it did not comply.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] On November 13, the Times-Picayune posted the video on its website.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] In March 2008, Levees.org announced that records obtained under the Freedom of Information Act revealed that as early October 2005, the Army Corps of Engineers had directed and later paid the ASCE more than $1.1 million for its peer review (Grant Number: W912HZ-06-1-0001).
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The grant also paid for a series of misleading ASCE presentations attempting to shift blame away from the corps and onto local levee officials.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Members of the ASCE are forbidden from making false or exaggerated statements and also from making statements for an interested party unless this is disclosed.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Levees.org claimed the records showed how the external peer review would be done in four phases: Phase 1 was research and analysis on the performance of the levees, floodwalls and other important structures.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Phase 2 was provision of information on the current system to prevent future flooding.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Phase 3 was provision of information to evaluate alternative approaches to flood protection.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Phase 4 was transfer information and knowledge gained to a broader audience within Corps and its consultancy community to communicate lessons learned.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The group claimed that these records were proof that ASCE's routine powerpoint presentation from 2007 and 2008 were a public relations campaign to repair the corps' reputation.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/american-society-of-civil-engineers] ASCE officials responded that ASCE paid for the powerpoint presentations itself and had not used USACE grant money for that purpose.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] An **architect** is a person who plans, designs, and oversees the construction of buildings.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] To practice architecture means to provide services in connection with the design of buildings and the space within the site surrounding the buildings that have human occupancy or use as their principal purpose.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] Etymologically, the term architect derives from the Latin *architectus*, which derives from the Greek (**arkhi*-*, chief + *tekton*, builder), i.e., chief builder.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] The professional requirements for architects vary from location to location.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] An architect's decisions affect public safety, and thus the architect must undergo specialised training consisting of advanced education and a *practicum* (or internship) for practical experience to earn a license to practice architecture.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] Practical, technical, and academic requirements for becoming an architect vary by jurisdiction though the formal study of architecture in academic institutions has played a pivotal role in the development of the profession.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] Throughout ancient and medieval history, most architectural design and construction was carried out by artisans—such as stone masons and carpenters—who rose to the role of master builders.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] Until modern times, there was no clear distinction between architect and engineer.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] In Europe, the titles *architect* and *engineer* were primarily geographical variations that referred to the same person, often used interchangeably.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] "Architect" derives from Greek ἀρχιτέκτων (*arkhitéktōn*, "master builder," "chief *tektōn*").
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] It is suggested that various developments in technology and mathematics allowed the development of the professional 'gentleman' architect, separate from the hands-on craftsman.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] Paper was not used in Europe for drawing until the 15th century but became increasingly available after 1500.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] The availability of both paper and pencils allowed pre-construction drawings to be made by professionals.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] Concurrently, the introduction of linear perspective and innovations such as the use of different projections to describe a three-dimensional building in two dimensions, together with an increased understanding of dimensional accuracy, helped building designers communicate their ideas.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] However, development was gradual and slow-going.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] Until the 18th century, buildings continued to be designed and set out by craftsmen, with the exception of high-status projects.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] In most developed countries only those qualified with an appropriate license, certification, or registration with a relevant body (often a government) may legally practice architecture.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] Such licensure usually requires a university degree, successful completion of exams, and a training period.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] Representation of oneself as an architect through the use of terms and titles were restricted to licensed individuals by law, although in general, derivatives such as architectural designer were not legally protected.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] To practice architecture implies the ability to practice independently of supervision.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] In many places, independent, non-licensed individuals may perform design services outside of professional restrictions, such as the design of houses or other smaller structures.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] In the architectural profession, technical and environmental knowledge, design, and construction management require an understanding of business as well as design.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] However, design is the driving force throughout the project and beyond.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] An architect accepts a commission from a client.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] The commission might involve preparing feasibility reports, building audits, and designing a building or several buildings, structures, and the spaces among them.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] The architect participates in developing the requirements the client wants in the building.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] Throughout the project (planning to occupancy), the architect coordinates a design team.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] Structural, mechanical, and electrical engineers are hired by the client or architect, who must ensure that the work is coordinated to construct the design.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] The architect, once hired by a client, is responsible for creating a design concept that meets the requirements of that client and provides a facility suitable for the required use.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] The architect must meet with and ask questions to the client, to ascertain all the requirements (and nuances) of the planned project.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] Often, the full brief is not clear in the beginning.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] It involves a degree of risk in the design undertaking.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] The architect may make early proposals to the client, which may rework the terms of the brief.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] The "program" (or brief) is essential to producing a project that meets all the needs of the owner.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] This becomes a guide for the architect in creating the design concept.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] Design proposals are generally expected to be both imaginative and pragmatic.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] Much depends upon the time, place, finance, culture, and available crafts and technology in which the design takes place.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] The extent and nature of these expectations will vary.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] Foresight is a prerequisite when designing buildings, as it is a very complex and demanding undertaking.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] The selection of appropriate materials and technology must be considered, tested, and reviewed at an early stage in the design to ensure there are no setbacks (such as higher-than-expected costs) that could occur later in the project.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] The site and its surrounding environment, as well as the culture and history of the place, will also influence the design.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] The design must also balance increasing concerns with environmental sustainability.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] The architect may introduce (intentionally or not), aspects of mathematics and architecture, new or current architectural theory, or references to architectural history.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] A key part of the design is that the architect often must consult with engineers, surveyors, and other specialists throughout the design, ensuring that aspects such as structural supports and air conditioning elements are coordinated.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] The control and planning of construction costs are also part of these consultations.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] Coordination of the different aspects involves a high degree of specialized communication, including advanced computer technology such as building information modeling (BIM), computer-aided design (CAD), and cloud-based technologies.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] Finally, at all times, the architect must report back to the client, who may have reservations or recommendations that might introduce further variables into the design.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] Architects also deal with local and federal jurisdictions regarding regulations and building codess.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] The architect might need to comply with local planning and zoning laws such as required setbacks, height limitations, parking requirements, transparency requirements (windows), and land use.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] Some jurisdictions require adherence to design and historic preservation guidelines.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] Health and safety risks form a vital part of the current design, and in some jurisdictions, design reports and records are required to include ongoing considerations of materials and contaminants, waste management and recycling, traffic control, and fire safety.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] Previously, architects employed drawings to illustrate and generate design proposals.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] While conceptual sketches are still widely used by architects, computer technology has now become the industry standard.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] Furthermore, design may include the use of photos, collages, prints, linocuts, 3D scanning technology, and other media in design production.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] Increasingly, computer software is shaping how architects work.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] BIM technology allows for the creation of a virtual building that serves as an information database for the sharing of design and building information throughout the life cycle of the building's design, construction, and maintenance.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] Virtual reality (VR) presentations are becoming more common for visualizing structural designs and interior spaces from the point-of-view perspective.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] Since modern buildings are known to release carbon into the atmosphere, increasing controls are being placed on buildings and associated technology to reduce emissions, increase energy efficiency, and make use of renewable energy sources.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] Renewable energy sources may be designed into the proposed building by local or national renewable energy providers.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] As a result, the architect is required to remain abreast of current regulations that are continually being updated.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] Some new developments exhibit extremely low energy use or passive solar building design.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] However, the architect is also increasingly being required to provide initiatives in a wider environmental sense.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] Examples of this include making provisions for low-energy transport, natural daylighting instead of artificial lighting, natural ventilation instead of air conditioning, pollution, and waste management, use of recycled materials, and employment of materials which can be easily recycled.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] As the design becomes more advanced and detailed, specifications and detail designs are made of all the elements and components of the building.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] Techniques in the production of a building are continually advancing which places a demand on the architect to ensure that he or she remains up to date with these advances.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] Architects typically put projects to tender on behalf of their clients, advise them on the award of the project to a general contractor, facilitate and administer a contract of agreement, which is often between the client and the contractor.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] This contract is legally binding and covers a wide range of aspects, including the insurance and commitments of all stakeholders, the status of the design documents, provisions for the architect's access, and procedures for the control of the works as they proceed.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] Depending on the type of contract used, provisions for further sub-contract tenders may be required.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] The architect may require that some elements be covered by a warranty which specifies the expected life and other aspects of the material, product, or work.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] In most jurisdictions prior notification to the relevant authority must be given before commencement of the project, giving the local authority notice to carry out independent inspections.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] The architect will then review and inspect the progress of the work in coordination with the local authority.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] In the United Kingdom and other countries, a quantity surveyor is often part of the team to provide cost consulting.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] With large, complex projects, an independent construction manager is sometimes hired to assist in the design and management of the construction.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] In many jurisdictions mandatory certification or assurance of the completed work or part of the work is required.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] This demand for certification entails a high degree of risk; therefore, regular inspections of the work as it progresses on site is required to ensure that the design is in compliance itself as well as following all relevant statutes and permissions.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] Recent decades have seen the rise of specialisations within the profession.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] Many architects and architectural firms focus on certain project types (e.g. healthcare, retail, public housing, and event management), technological expertise, or project delivery methods.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] Some architects specialise in building code, building envelope, sustainable design, technical writing, historic preservation (US) or conservation (UK), and accessibility.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] Many architects elect to move into real-estate (property) development, corporate facilities planning, project management, construction management, chief sustainability officers interior design, city planning, user experience design, and design research.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] Although there are variations in each location, most of the world's architects are required to register with the appropriate jurisdiction.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] Architects are typically required to meet three common requirements: education, experience, and examination.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] Basic educational requirements generally consist of a university degree in architecture.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] The experience requirement for degree candidates is usually satisfied by a practicum or internship (most often two to three years).
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] Finally, a Registration Examination or a series of exams is required prior to licensure.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] Professionals who engaged in the design and supervision of construction projects before the late 19th century were not necessarily trained in a separate architecture program in an academic setting.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] Instead, they often trained under established architects.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] Prior to modern times, there was no distinction between architects and engineers and the title used varied depending on geographical location.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] They often carried the title of master builder or surveyor after serving a number of years as an apprentice (such as Sir Christopher Wren).
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] The formal study of architecture in academic institutions played a pivotal role in the development of the profession as a whole, serving as a focal point for advances in architectural technology and theory.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] The use of "Architect" or abbreviations such as "Ar." as a title attached to a person's name was regulated by law in some countries.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] Architects' fee structure is typically based on a percentage of construction value, as a rate per unit area of the proposed construction, hourly rates, or a fixed lump sum fee.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] Combination of these structures is also common.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] Fixed fees are usually based on a project's allocated construction cost and could range between 4 and 12% of new construction cost for commercial and institutional projects, depending on the project's size and complexity.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] Residential projects range from 12 to 20%.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] Renovation projects typically command higher percentages such as 15–20%.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] Overall billings for architectural firms range widely, depending on their location and economic climate.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] Billings have traditionally been dependent on local economic conditions, but with rapid globalization, this is becoming less of a factor for large international firms.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] Salaries could also vary depending on experience, position within the firm (i.e. staff architect, partner, or shareholder, etc.), and the size and location of the firm.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] A number of national professional organizations exist to promote career and business development in architecture.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] A wide variety of prizes is awarded by national professional associations and other bodies, recognizing accomplished architects, their buildings, structures, and professional careers.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] The most lucrative award an architect can receive is the Pritzker Prize, sometimes termed the "Nobel Prize for architecture".
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] The inaugural Pritzker Prize winner was Philip Johnson who was cited as having "50 years of imagination and vitality embodied in a myriad of museums, theatres libraries, houses gardens and corporate structures".
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] The Pritzker Prize has been awarded for forty-two straight editions without interruption, and there are now 22 countries with at least one winning architect.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] Other prestigious architectural awards are the Royal Gold Medal, the AIA Gold Medal (US), AIA Gold Medal (Australia), and the Praemium Imperiale.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] Those elected to chartered membership of the RIBA after 1971 may use the initials RIBA but cannot use the old ARIBA and FRIBA.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] An honorary fellow may use the initials Hon.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] FRIBA, and an international fellow may use the initials Int.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] Architects in the US who have made contributions to the profession through design excellence or architectural education or have in some other way advanced the profession are elected Fellows of the American Institute of Architects and can write FAIA after their name.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architect] In Hong Kong, those elected to chartered membership may use the initial HKIA, and those who have made a special contribution after nomination and election by the Hong Kong Institute of Architects (HKIA), may be elected as fellow members of HKIA and may use FHKIA after their name.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] From reduction of greenhouse gas emissions to the construction of resilient buildings, architectural engineers are at the forefront of addressing several major challenges of the 21st century.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] They apply the latest scientific knowledge and technologies to the design of buildings.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] Architectural engineering as a relatively new licensed profession emerged in the 20th century as a result of the rapid technological developments.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] Architectural engineers are at the forefront of two major historical opportunities that today's world is immersed in: (1) that of rapidly advancing computer-technology, and (2) the parallel revolution of environmental sustainability.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] Architects and architectural engineers both play crucial roles in building design and construction, but they focus on different aspects.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] Architectural engineers specialize in the technical and structural aspects, ensuring buildings are safe, efficient, and sustainable.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] Their education blends architecture with engineering, focusing on structural integrity, mechanical systems, and energy efficiency.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] They design and analyze building systems, conduct feasibility studies, and collaborate with architects to integrate technical requirements into the overall design.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] Architects, on the other hand, emphasize the aesthetic, functional, and spatial elements, developing design concepts and detailed plans to meet client needs and comply with regulations.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] Their education focuses on design theory, history, and artistic aspects, and they oversee the construction process to ensure the design is correctly implemented.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] Mechanical engineering and electrical engineering engineers are specialists when engaged in the building design fields.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] This is known as mechanical, electrical, and plumbing (MEP) throughout the United States, or building services engineering in the United Kingdom, Canada, and Australia.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] Mechanical engineers often design and oversee the heating, ventilation and air conditioning (HVAC), plumbing, and rainwater systems.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] Plumbing designers often include design specifications for simple active fire protection systems, but for more complicated projects, fire protection engineers are often separately retained.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] Electrical engineers are responsible for the building's electric power distribution, telecommunication, fire alarm, signalization, lightning protection and control systems, as well as lighting systems.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] Structural engineering involves the analysis and design of the built environment (buildings, bridges, equipment supports, towers and walls).
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] Those concentrating on buildings are sometimes informally referred to as "building engineers".
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] Architectural engineers sometimes incorporate structural as one aspect of their designs; the structural discipline when practiced as a specialty works closely with architects and other engineering specialists.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] Sustainable engineering involves designing or operating systems to use energy and resources in a way that maintains environmental balance and ensures that future generations can meet their own needs without compromising the natural environment.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] Architectural engineers are influenced by sustainable engineering principles in their education, training, and practice, integrating sustainable design strategies to create buildings and structures that minimize environmental impact and enhance energy efficiency.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] Building enclosure and façade engineering involves the design and management of the outer shell of a building, which acts as a barrier between the interior and exterior environments.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] This includes walls, roofs, windows, doors, and other components that collectively ensure the building is protected from external elements such as air, water, heat, light, and noise.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] The building envelope plays a crucial role in maintaining indoor comfort by controlling temperature, humidity, and airflow.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] It also contributes to the building's energy efficiency by minimizing heat loss in the winter and heat gain in the summer.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] Engineers in this field work on making sure the envelope is structurally sound, aesthetically pleasing, and performs effectively to meet various functional requirements.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] Fire protection engineering is a subfield of building engineering focused on the design and application of systems and practices that prevent, control, and mitigate the impact of fires.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] This discipline aims to protect people, property, and the environment from the destructive effects of fire through a combination of preventive measures, detection systems, and response strategies.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] Fire protection engineers use their expertise to analyze potential fire scenarios, model the spread of fire and smoke, and design systems that effectively protect lives and property.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] They collaborate with architects, builders, and safety officials to integrate fire protection measures into the overall design and operation of buildings and facilities.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] Acoustical or acoustics engineering in building design focuses on controlling sound within and around buildings to create a comfortable and functional auditory environment.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] This discipline involves the study and application of principles to manage noise levels, improve sound quality, and ensure effective sound insulation.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] Acoustical engineers work closely with architects, builders, and other engineers to integrate sound control measures into the overall design of a building.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] They use advanced modeling and simulation tools to predict how sound will behave in different spaces and employ various materials and techniques to achieve the desired acoustic performance.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] Their goal is to create environments that are acoustically comfortable, meeting the specific needs of the building's occupants and its intended use.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] In many jurisdictions of the United States, the architectural engineer is a licensed engineering professional.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] Although some states require a BS degree from an EAC/ABET-accredited engineering program, with no exceptions, about two thirds of the states accept BS degrees from ETAC/ABET-accredited architectural engineering technology programs to become licensed engineering professionals.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] Architectural engineering technology graduates, with applied engineering skills, often gain further learning with an MS degree in engineering and/or NAAB-accredited Masters of Architecture to become licensed as both an engineer and architect.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] This path requires the individual to pass state licensing exams in both disciplines.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] States handle this situation differently on experienced gained working under a licensed engineer and/or registered architect prior to taking the examinations.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] This education model is more in line with the educational system in the United Kingdom where an accredited MEng or MS degree in engineering for further learning is required by the Engineering Council to be registered as a Chartered Engineer.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] The National Council of Architectural Registration Boards (NCARB) facilitate the licensure and credentialing of architects but requirements for registration often vary between states.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] In the state of New Jersey, a registered architect is allowed to sit for the PE exam and a professional engineer is allowed to take the design portions of the Architectural Registration Exam (ARE), to become a registered architect.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] Formal architectural engineering education, following the engineering model of earlier disciplines, developed in the late 19th century, and became widespread in the United States by the mid-20th century.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] With the establishment of a specific "architectural engineering" NCEES Professional Engineering registration examination in the 1990s, and first offering in April 2003, architectural engineering became recognized as a distinct engineering discipline in the United States.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] Up to date NCEES account allows engineers to apply to other states PE license "by comity".
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] In most license-regulated jurisdictions, architectural engineers are not entitled to practice architecture unless they are also licensed as architects.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] Practice of structural engineering in high-risk locations, e.g., due to strong earthquakes, or on specific types of higher importance buildings such as hospitals, may require separate licensing as well.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] Regulations and customary practice vary widely by state or city.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] In some countries, the practice of architecture includes planning, designing and overseeing the building's construction, and architecture, as a profession providing architectural services, is referred to as "architectural engineering".
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] In Japan, a "first-class architect" plays the dual role of architect and building engineer, although the services of a licensed "structural design first-class architect"(構造設計一級建築士) are required for buildings over a certain scale.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] In some languages, such as Korean and Arabic, "architect" is literally translated as "architectural engineer".
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] In some countries, an "architectural engineer" (such as the *ingegnere edile* in Italy) is entitled to practice architecture and is often referred to as an architect.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] These individuals are often also structural engineers.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] In other countries, such as Germany, Austria, Iran, and most of the Arab countries, architecture graduates receive an engineering degree (*Dipl.-Ing. – Diplom-Ingenieur*).
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] In Spain, an "architect" has a technical university education and legal powers to carry out building structure and facility projects.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] In Brazil, architects and engineers used to share the same accreditation process (Conselho Federal de Engenheiros, Arquitetos e Agrônomos (CONFEA) – Federal Council of Engineering, Architecture and Agronomy).
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] Now the Brazilian architects and urbanists have their own accreditation process (CAU – Architecture and Urbanism Council).
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] Besides traditional architecture design training, Brazilian architecture courses also offer complementary training in engineering disciplines such as structural, electrical, hydraulic and mechanical engineering.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] In Greece licensed architectural engineers are graduates from architecture faculties that belong to the Polytechnic University, obtaining an "Engineering Diploma".
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] They graduate after 5 years of studies and are fully entitled architects once they become members of the Technical Chamber of Greece (TEE – Τεχνικό Επιμελητήριο Ελλάδος).
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] The Technical Chamber of Greece has more than 100,000 members encompassing all the engineering disciplines as well as architecture.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] A prerequisite for being a member is to be licensed as a qualified engineer or architect and to be a graduate of an engineering and architecture schools of a Greek university, or of an equivalent school from abroad.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] The Technical Chamber of Greece is the authorized body to provide work licenses to engineers of all disciplines as well as architects, graduated in Greece or abroad.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] The license is awarded after examinations.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] The examinations take place three to four times a year.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] The Engineering Diploma equals a master's degree in ECTS units (300) according to the Bologna Accords.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] The architectural, structural, mechanical and electrical engineering branches each have well established educational requirements that are usually fulfilled by completion of a university program.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] In Canada, a CEAB-accredited engineer degree is the minimum academic requirement for registration as a P.Eng (professional engineer) anywhere in Canada and the standard against which all other engineering academic qualifications are measured.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] A graduate of a non-CEAB-accredited program must demonstrate that his or her education is at least equivalent to that of a graduate of a CEAB-accredited program.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] In Vietnam, the engineer's degree is called *Bằng kỹ sư*, the first degree after five years of study.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] The Ministry of Education of Vietnam has also issued separate regulations for the naming of degrees not in accordance with international regulation.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] Its multi-disciplinary engineering approach is what differentiates architectural engineering from architecture (the field of the architect): which is an integrated, separate and single, field of study when compared to other engineering disciplines.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] Through training in and appreciation of architecture, the field seeks integration of building systems within its overall building design.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] Architectural engineering includes the design of building systems including heating, ventilation and air conditioning (HVAC), plumbing, fire protection, electrical, lighting, architectural acoustics, and structural systems.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-engineering] In some university programs, students are required to concentrate on one of the systems; in others, they can receive a generalist architectural or building engineering degree.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-style] An **architectural style** is a classification of buildings (and building structures) based on 84 of characteristics and features, including overall appearance, arrangement of the components, method of construction, building materials used, form, size, structural sign, and regional character.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-style] Architectural styles are frequently associated with a historical epoch (Renaissance style), geographical location (Italian Villa style), or an earlier architectural style (Neo-Gothic style), and are influenced by the corresponding broader artistic style and the "general human condition".
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-style] Heinrich Wölfflin even declared an analogy between a building and a costume: an "architectural style reflects the *attitude and the movement of people* in the period concerned".
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-style] The 21st century construction uses a multitude of styles that are sometimes lumped together as a "contemporary architecture" based on the common trait of extreme reliance on computer-aided architectural design (cf.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-style] Folk architecture (also "vernacular architecture") is not a style, but an application of local customs to small-scale construction without clear identity of the builder.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-style] The concept of architectural style is studied in the architectural history as one of the approaches ("style and period") that are used to organize the history of architecture (Leach lists five other approaches as "biography, geography and culture, type, technique, theme and analogy").
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-style] Style provides an additional relationship between otherwise disparate buildings, thus serving as a "protection against chaos".
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-style] The concept of style was foreign to architects until the 18th century.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-style] Prior to the era of Enlightenment, the architectural form was mostly considered timeless, either as a divine revelation or an absolute truth derived from the laws of nature, and a great architect was the one who understood this "language".
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-style] The new interpretation of history declared each historical period to be a stage of growth for the humanity (cf.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-style] Johann Gottfried Herder's *Volksgeist* that much later developed into *Zeitgeist*).
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-style] This approach allowed to classify architecture of each age as an equally valid approach, "style" (the use of the word in this sense became established by the mid-18th century).
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-style] Style has been subject of an extensive debate since at least the 19th century.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-style] Many architects argue that the notion of "style" cannot adequately describe the contemporary architecture, is obsolete and ridden with historicism.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-style] In their opinion, by concentrating on the appearance of the building, style classification misses the hidden from view ideas that architects had put into the form.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-style] Studying history of architecture without reliance on styles usually relies on a "canon" of important architects and buildings.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-style] The lesser objects in this approach do not deserve attention: "A bicycle shed is a building; Lincoln Cathedral is a piece of architecture" (Nikolaus Pevsner, 1943).
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-style] Nonetheless, the traditional and popular approach to the architectural history is through chronology of styles, with changes reflecting the evolution of materials, economics, fashions, and beliefs.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-style] Works of architecture are unlikely to be preserved for their aesthetic value alone; with practical re-purposing, the original intent of the original architect, sometimes his very identity, can be forgotten, and the building style becomes "an indispensable historical tool".
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-style] Styles emerge from the history of a society.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-style] At any time several styles may be fashionable, and when a style changes it usually does so gradually, as architects learn and adapt to new ideas.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-style] The new style is sometimes only a rebellion against an existing style, such as postmodern architecture (meaning "after modernism"), which in 21st century has found its own language and split into a number of styles which have acquired other names.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-style] Architectural styles often spread to other places, so that the style at its source continues to develop in new ways while other countries follow with their own twist.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-style] For instance, Renaissance ideas emerged in Italy around 1425 and spread to all of Europe over the next 200 years, with the French, German, English, and Spanish Renaissances showing recognisably the same style, but with unique characteristics.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-style] An architectural style may also spread through colonialism, either by foreign colonies learning from their home country, or by settlers moving to a new land.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-style] One example is the Spanish missions in California, brought by Spanish priests in the late 18th century and built in a unique style.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-style] After an architectural style has gone out of fashion, revivals and re-interpretations may occur.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-style] For instance, classicism has been revived many times and found new life as neoclassicism.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-style] Each time it is revived, it is different.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-style] The Spanish mission style was revived 100 years later as the Mission Revival, and that soon evolved into the Spanish Colonial Revival.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-style] Early writing on the subjects of architectural history, since the works of Vitruvius in the 1st century B.C., treated architecture as a patrimony that was passed on to the next generation of architects by their forefathers.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-style] Giorgio Vasari in the 16th century shifted the narrative to biographies of the great artists in his "Lives of the Most Excellent Painters, Sculptors, and Architects".
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-style] Constructing schemes of the period styles of historic art and architecture was a major concern of 19th century scholars in the new and initially mostly German-speaking field of art history.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-style] Important writers on the broad theory of style including Carl Friedrich von Rumohr, Gottfried Semper, and Alois Riegl in his *Stilfragen* of 1893, with Heinrich Wölfflin and Paul Frankl continued the debate into the 20th century.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-style] Paul Jacobsthal and Josef Strzygowski are among the art historians who followed Riegl in proposing grand schemes tracing the transmission of elements of styles across great ranges in time and space.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-style] This type of art history is also known as formalism, or the study of forms or shapes in art.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-style] Wölfflin declared the goal of formalism as German: *Kunstgeschichtliche Grundbegriffe*, "art history without names", where an architect's work has a place in history that is independent of its author.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-style] The subject of study no longer was the ideas that Borromini borrowed from Maderno who in turn learned from Michelangelo, instead the questions now were about the continuity and changes observed when the architecture transitioned from Renaissance to Baroque.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-style] Terms originated to describe architectural periods were often subsequently applied to other areas of the visual arts, and then more widely still to music, literature and the general culture.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-style] In architecture stylistic change often follows, and is made possible by, the discovery of new techniques or materials, from the Gothic rib vault to modern metal and reinforced concrete construction.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-style] According to James Elkins "In the later 20th century criticisms of style were aimed at further reducing the Hegelian elements of the concept while retaining it in a form that could be more easily controlled".
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architectural-style] In the middle of the 19th century, multiple aesthetic and social factors forced architects to design the new buildings using a selection of styles patterned after the historical ones (working "in every style or none"), and style definition became a practical matter.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] The practice of architecture itself, which began in the prehistoric era, has been used as a way of expressing culture by civilizations on all seven continents.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] For this reason, architecture is considered to be a form of art.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Texts on architecture have been written since ancient times.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] The earliest surviving text on architectural theories is the 1st century BC treatise *De architectura* by the Roman architect Vitruvius, according to whom a good building embodies *firmitas, utilitas*, and *venustas* (durability, utility, and beauty).
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Centuries later, Leon Battista Alberti developed his ideas further, seeing beauty as an objective quality of buildings to be found in their proportions.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] In the 19th century, Louis Sullivan declared that "form follows function".
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] "Function" began to replace the classical "utility" and was understood to include not only practical but also aesthetic, psychological, and cultural dimensions.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] The idea of sustainable architecture was introduced in the late 20th century.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Architecture began as rural, oral vernacular architecture that developed from trial and error to successful replication.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Ancient urban architecture was preoccupied with building religious structures and buildings symbolizing the political power of rulers until Greek and Roman architecture shifted focus to civic virtues.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Indian and Chinese architecture influenced forms all over Asia and Buddhist architecture in particular took diverse local flavors.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] During the Middle Ages, pan-European styles of Romanesque and Gothic cathedrals and abbeys emerged while the Renaissance favored Classical forms implemented by architects known by name.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Later, the roles of architects and engineers became separated.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Modern architecture began after World War I as an avant-garde movement that sought to develop a completely new style appropriate for a new post-war social and economic order focused on meeting the needs of the middle and working classes.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Emphasis was put on modern techniques, materials, and simplified geometric forms, paving the way for high-rise superstructures.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Many architects became disillusioned with modernism which they perceived as ahistorical and anti-aesthetic, and postmodern and contemporary architecture developed.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Over the years, the field of architectural construction has branched out to include everything from ship design to interior decorating.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] The philosophy of architecture is a branch of the philosophy of art, dealing with aesthetic value of architecture, its semantics and its relation to the development of culture.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Many philosophers and theoreticians from Plato to Michel Foucault, Gilles Deleuze, Robert Venturi and Ludwig Wittgenstein have concerned themselves with the nature of architecture and whether or not architecture is distinguished from building.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] The earliest surviving written work on the subject of architecture is *De architectura* by the Roman architect Vitruvius in the early 1st century BC.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] According to Vitruvius, a good building should satisfy the three principles of *firmitas, utilitas, venustas*, commonly known by the original translation – *firmness, commodity and delight*.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] According to Vitruvius, the architect should strive to fulfill each of these three attributes as well as possible.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Leon Battista Alberti, who elaborates on the ideas of Vitruvius in his treatise, *De re aedificatoria*, saw beauty primarily as a matter of proportion, although ornament also played a part.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] For Alberti, the rules of proportion were those that governed the idealized human figure, the golden mean.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] The most important aspect of beauty was, therefore, an inherent part of an object, rather than something applied superficially, and was based on universal, recognizable truths.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] The notion of style in the arts was not developed until the 16th century, with the writing of Giorgio Vasari.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] By the 18th century, his *Lives of the Most Excellent Painters, Sculptors, and Architects* had been translated into Italian, French, Spanish, and English.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] In the 16th century, Italian Mannerist architect, painter and theorist Sebastiano Serlio wrote *Tutte L'Opere D'Architettura et Prospetiva* (*Complete Works on Architecture and Perspective*).
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] This treatise exerted immense influence throughout Europe, being the first handbook that emphasized the practical rather than the theoretical aspects of architecture, and it was the first to catalog the five orders.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] In the early 19th century, Augustus Welby Northmore Pugin wrote *Contrasts* (1836) that, as the title suggested, contrasted the modern, industrial world, which he disparaged, with an idealized image of neo-medieval world.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Gothic architecture, Pugin believed, was the only "true Christian form of architecture." The 19th-century English art critic, John Ruskin, in his *Seven Lamps of Architecture*, published 1849, was much narrower in his view of what constituted architecture.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Architecture was the "art which so disposes and adorns the edifices raised by men ... that the sight of them" contributes "to his mental health, power, and pleasure".
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] For Ruskin, the aesthetic was of overriding significance.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] His work goes on to state that a building is not truly a work of architecture unless it is in some way "adorned".
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] For Ruskin, a well-constructed, well-proportioned, functional building needed string courses or rustication, at the very least.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] On the difference between the ideals of *architecture* and mere *construction*, the 20th-century architect Le Corbusier wrote: "You employ stone, wood, and concrete, and with these materials you build houses and palaces: that is construction.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] But suddenly you touch my heart, you do me good.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] I am happy and I say: This is beautiful.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Le Corbusier's contemporary Ludwig Mies van der Rohe is said to have stated in a 1959 interview that "architecture starts when you carefully put two bricks together.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] The notable 19th-century architect of skyscrapers, Louis Sullivan, promoted an overriding precept to architectural design: "Form follows function".
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] While the notion that structural and aesthetic considerations should be entirely subject to functionality was met with both popularity and skepticism, it introduced the concept of "function" in place of Vitruvius' "utility".
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] "Function" came to be seen as encompassing all criteria of the use, perception and enjoyment of a building, not only practical but also aesthetic, psychological and cultural.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Nunzia Rondanini stated, "Through its aesthetic dimension architecture goes beyond the functional aspects that it has in common with other human sciences.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Through its own particular way of expressing values, architecture can stimulate and influence social life without presuming that, in and of itself, it will promote social development....
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] To restrict the meaning of (architectural) formalism to art for art's sake is not only reactionary; it can also be a purposeless quest for perfection or originality which degrades form into a mere instrumentality".
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] The aesthetics of architecture remain a contested topic.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Differences in aesthetic preferences between architects and the public were found.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Studies generally find that there is a strong public preference for traditional and classical architectural styles over modernist designs.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] James Stevens Curl argues that modernist architects often favour designs that are alienating and environmentally damaging.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Léon Krier frames the dominance of traditional styles in private architecture as an "overwhelming democratic reality," contrasting with the prevalence of modernist designs in public commissions.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Among the philosophies that have influenced modern architects and their approach to building design are Rationalism, Empiricism, Structuralism, Poststructuralism, Deconstruction and Phenomenology.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] In the late 20th century a new concept was added to those included in the compass of both structure and function, the consideration of sustainability, hence sustainable architecture.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Building first evolved out of the dynamics between needs (e.g. shelter, security, and worship) and means (available building materials and attendant skills).
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] As human cultures developed and knowledge began to be formalized through oral traditions and practices, building became a craft, and *architecture* became the term used to describe the highly formalized and respected aspects of the craft.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] It is widely assumed that architectural success was achieved through trial and error, with progressively less trial and more replication as results became satisfactory over time.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] However, vernacular architecture, in essence a rudimentary, non-academic form of building construction based on cultural traditions, continues to be produced in many parts of the world.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Early human settlements were mostly rural.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Expanding economies resulted in the creation of proto-cities or urban areas, which in some cases grew and evolved very rapidly, such as Çatalhöyük in modern-day Turkey and Mohenjo-daro in modern-day Pakistan.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Neolithic archaeological sites include Göbekli Tepe and Çatalhöyük in Turkey, Jericho in the Levant, Mehrgarh in Pakistan, Skara Brae in Orkney, and Cucuteni-Trypillian culture settlements in Romania, Moldova and Ukraine.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] In Egypt, the education of state architects was closely linked to the priestly class, and trade secrets were passed from father to son.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Plans were drawn and then implemented using the ruler, square, and triangle.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] The architecture and urbanism of classical civilizations such as the Greek and Roman civilizations evolved from civic ideals rather than religious or empirical ones.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] New building types emerged and architectural style developed in the form of the classical orders.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Roman architecture was influenced by Greek architecture as they incorporated many Greek elements into their building practices.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Texts on architecture have been written since ancient times—these texts provided both general advice and specific formal prescriptions or canons.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Some examples of canons are found in the writings of Vitruvius in the 1st century BC.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Some of the most important early examples of canonic architecture are religious.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Asian architecture developed differently from European architecture, and the Buddhist, Hindu and Sikh architectural styles have different characteristics.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Unlike Indian and Chinese architecture, which had great influence on the surrounding regions, Japanese architecture did not.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Some Asian architecture showed great regional diversity, in particular Buddhist architecture.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Moreover, another architectural achievement in Asia is the Hindu temple architecture, which developed from around the 5th century CE.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] It is, in theory, governed by concepts laid down in the Shastras, and is concerned with expressing both the macrocosm and the microcosm.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] In many Asian countries, pantheistic religion led to architectural forms that were designed specifically to enhance the natural landscape.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Also, the grandest houses were relatively lightweight structures mainly using wood until recent times, and there are few survivals of great age.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Buddhism was associated with a move to stone and brick religious structures, probably beginning as rock-cut architecture, which has often survived very well.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Early Asian writings on architecture include the *Kao Gong Ji* of China from the 7th–5th centuries BC, the Shilpa Shastras of ancient India, Manjusri Vasthu Vidya Sastra of Sri Lanka, and Araniko of Nepal.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] The Architecture of Africa is very diverse, reflecting the continent’s many climates, cultures, and histories.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Traditional African architecture mixes building traditions, using a wide arrange of materials like mud, stone, and wood.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Fractal scaling is commonly used in designs, making smaller parts of a structure mirror the overall design.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] This concept can be seen in village layouts and decorative elements.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Historical stone structures like the great Zimbabwe walls show the long lasting and durable construction.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Wattle and Daub is a technique used in many areas that take wooden frames covered in mud to create rounded structures that help to regulate the temperature inside.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Architecture in West Africa such as Porto-Novo in Benin, Lagos Island and Zaria in Nigeria and Dakar in Senegal is dominated by the Sudano-Sahelian, Afro-modernist designs and Sobrado styles.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] This is a form of multi-storied, Portuguese-Brazilian baroque architecture.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] These buildings are suited for dry, hot climates, as they often have central or rear courtyard, stuccoed façades, symmetrical layouts, tiled roofs for heat insulation, and prominent balconies.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Along the Swahili Coast of East Africa many homes are made out of coral stone with mangrove pole roofs.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] The architecture is a mix of local, Arabic and Islamic styles due to trade across the Indian Ocean.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Ethiopia also has stunning architectural traditions like the rock-hewn churches like the 13th century churches of Lalibela which were carved directly into the ground.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Together, these styles highlight the creativity, adaptability, and cultural depth of African architectural traditions.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Islamic architecture began in the 7th century, incorporating architectural forms from the ancient Middle East and Byzantium, but also developing features to suit the religious and social needs of the society.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Examples can be found throughout the Middle East, Africa, Iberian Peninsula, the Mediterranean islands, the Indian Sub-continent and later in Eastern parts of Europe, such as the Balkan States, as the result of the expansion of the Ottoman Empire.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] In Europe during the Medieval period, guilds were formed by craftsmen to organize their trades and written contracts have survived, particularly in relation to ecclesiastical buildings.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] The role of architect was usually one with that of master mason, or *Magister lathomorum* as they are sometimes described in contemporary documents.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] The major architectural undertakings were the building of abbeys and cathedrals.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] From about 900 onward, the movements of both clerics and tradesmen carried architectural knowledge across Europe, resulting in the pan-European styles Romanesque and Gothic.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] A significant part of the Middle Ages architectural heritage is numerous fortifications across the continent.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] From the Balkans to Spain, and from Malta to Estonia, these buildings represent an important part of European heritage.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] In Renaissance Europe, from about 1400 onwards, there was a revival of Classical learning accompanied by the development of Renaissance humanism, which placed greater emphasis on the role of the individual in society than had been the case during the Medieval period.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Buildings were ascribed to specific architects – Brunelleschi, Alberti, Michelangelo, Palladio – and the cult of the individual had begun.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] There was still no dividing line between artist, architect, engineer, or any of the related vocations, and the appellation was often one of regional preference.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] A revival of the Classical style in architecture was accompanied by a burgeoning of science and engineering, which affected the proportions and structure of buildings.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] At this stage, it was still possible for an artist to design a bridge as the level of structural calculations involved was within the scope of the generalist.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] With the emerging knowledge in scientific fields and the rise of new materials and technology, architecture and engineering began to separate, and the architect began to concentrate on aesthetics and the humanist aspects, often at the expense of technical aspects of building design.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Formal architectural training in the 19th century, for example, at École des Beaux-Arts in France, gave much emphasis to the production of beautiful drawings and little to context and feasibility.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Meanwhile, the Industrial Revolution laid open the door for mass production and consumption.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Aesthetics became a criterion for the middle class as ornamented products, once within the province of expensive craftsmanship, became cheaper under machine production.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Vernacular architecture became increasingly ornamental.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Housebuilders could use current architectural design in their work by combining features found in pattern books and architectural journals.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Around the beginning of the 20th century, general dissatisfaction with the emphasis on revivalist architecture and elaborate decoration gave rise to many new lines of thought that served as precursors to Modern architecture.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Notable among these is the Deutscher Werkbund, formed in 1907 to produce better quality machine-made objects.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] The rise of the profession of industrial design is usually placed here.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Following this lead, the Bauhaus school, founded in Weimar, Germany in 1919, redefined the architectural bounds prior set throughout history, viewing the creation of a building as the ultimate synthesis – the apex – of art, craft, and technology.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] When modern architecture was first practiced, it was an avant-garde movement with moral, philosophical, and aesthetic underpinnings.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Immediately after World War I, pioneering modernist architects sought to develop a completely new style appropriate for a new post-war social and economic order focused on meeting the needs of the middle and working classes.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] They rejected the architectural practice of the academic refinement of historical styles which served the rapidly declining aristocratic order.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] The approach of the Modernist architects was to reduce buildings to pure forms, removing historical references and ornament in favor of functional details.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Buildings displayed their functional and structural elements, exposing steel beams and concrete surfaces instead of hiding them behind decorative forms.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Architects such as Frank Lloyd Wright developed organic architecture, in which the form was defined by its environment and purpose, with an aim to promote harmony between human habitation and the natural world with prime examples being Robie House and Fallingwater.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Fazlur Rahman Khan's development of the tube structure was a technological breakthrough in building ever higher.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] By mid-century, Modernism had morphed into the International Style, an aesthetic epitomized in many ways by the Twin Towers of New York's World Trade Center designed by Minoru Yamasaki.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Many architects resisted modernism, finding it devoid of the decorative richness of historical styles.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] As the first generation of modernists began to die after World War II, the second generation of architects including Paul Rudolph, Marcel Breuer, and Eero Saarinen tried to expand the aesthetics of modernism with Brutalism, buildings with expressive sculpture façades made of unfinished concrete.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] But an even younger postwar generation critiqued modernism and Brutalism for being too austere, standardized, monotone, and not taking into account the richness of human experience offered in historical buildings across time and in different places and cultures.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] One such reaction to the cold aesthetic of modernism and Brutalism is the school of metaphoric architecture, which includes such things as bio morphism and zoomorphic architecture, both using nature as the primary source of inspiration and design.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] While it is considered by some to be merely an aspect of postmodernism, others consider it to be a school in its own right and a later development of expressionist architecture.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Postmodernism produced a style that combined contemporary building technology and cheap materials with the aesthetics of older pre-modern and non-modern styles, from high classical architecture to popular or vernacular regional building styles.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Robert Venturi famously defined postmodern architecture as a "decorated shed" (an ordinary building which is functionally designed inside and embellished on the outside) and upheld it against modernist and brutalist "ducks" (buildings with unnecessarily expressive tectonic forms).
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Since the 1980s, as the complexity of buildings began to increase (in terms of structural systems, services, energy and technologies), the field of architecture became multi-disciplinary with specializations for each project type, technological expertise or project delivery methods.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Moreover, there has been an increased separation of the 'design' architect from the 'project' architect who ensures that the project meets the required standards and deals with matters of liability.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] The preparatory processes for the design of any large building have become increasingly complicated, and require preliminary studies of such matters as durability, sustainability, quality, money, and compliance with local laws.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] A large structure can no longer be the design of one person but must be the work of many.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Environmental sustainability has become a mainstream issue, with a profound effect on the architectural profession.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Many developers, those who support the financing of buildings, have become educated to encourage the facilitation of environmentally sustainable design, rather than solutions based primarily on immediate cost.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Major examples of this can be found in passive solar building design, greener roof designs, biodegradable materials, and more attention to a structure's energy usage.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] This major shift in architecture has also changed architecture schools to focus more on the environment.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] There has been an acceleration in the number of buildings that seek to meet green building sustainable design principles.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Sustainable practices that were at the core of vernacular architecture increasingly provide inspiration for environmentally and socially sustainable contemporary techniques.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Green Building Council's LEED (Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design) rating system has been influential in this.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Concurrently, the recent movements of New Urbanism, Metaphoric architecture, contemporary Traditional architecture and New Classical architecture promote a sustainable approach towards construction that appreciates and develops smart growth, architectural tradition, and classical design.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] This in contrast to modernist and globally uniform architecture, as well as leaning against solitary housing estates and suburban sprawl.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Glass curtain walls, which were the hallmark of the ultra modern urban life in many countries, surfaced even in developing countries like Nigeria where international styles had been represented since the mid-20th Century, mostly because of the leanings of foreign-trained architects.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Residential architecture is the design which functionally fits the user's lifestyle while adhering to the building codes and zoning laws.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Commercial architecture is the design of commercial buildings that serves the needs of businesses, the government, and religious institutions.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Industrial architecture is the design of specialized industrial buildings, whose primary focus is designing buildings that can fulfil their function while ensuring the safe movement of labor and goods in the facility.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Landscape architecture is the design of outdoor public areas, landmarks, and structures to achieve environmental, social-behavioral, or aesthetic outcomes.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] It involves the systematic investigation of existing social, ecological, and soil conditions and processes in the landscape and the design of interventions that will produce the desired outcome.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] A practitioner in the profession of landscape architecture is called a landscape architect.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Interior architecture is the design of a space which has been created by structural boundaries and the human interaction within these boundaries.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] It can also be the initial design and plan for use, then later redesigned to accommodate a changed purpose or a significantly revised design for adaptive reuse of the building shell.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] The latter is often part of sustainable architecture practices, conserving resources through "recycling" a structure by adaptive redesign.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Generally referred to as the spatial art of environmental design, form and practice, interior architecture is the process through which the interiors of buildings are designed, concerned with all aspects of the human uses of structural spaces.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Urban design is the process of designing and shaping the physical features of cities, towns, and villages.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Urban design is an interdisciplinary field that uses elements of many built environment professions, including landscape architecture, urban planning, architecture, civil engineering and municipal engineering.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] It is common for professionals in all these disciplines to practice urban design.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] In more recent times different sub-subfields of urban design have emerged such as strategic urban design, landscape urbanism, water-sensitive urban design, and sustainable urbanism.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Green Building is about the structure and application process of minimizing the environmental impact of buildings.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Interest in sustainable design grew after the 1973 oil embargo which highlighted the need for policies like the Clean Water Act and the creation of the Environmental Protection Agency.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] This motivated a small group of architects that were passionate and environmentally conscious to start designing more sustainably.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Green Design uses renewable energy strategies like, green roofs, passive heating/cooling, and reduced materials help to create sustainable and high-performance structures that blend with the nature around them.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Sustainable materials like reclaimed wood, bamboo, and recycled materials are used to limit resource waste.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Water conservation is another key strategy, utilizing systems that make sure to harvest rainwater and recycle greywater.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Architects also orientate buildings to take advantage of the climate utilizing the sun for natural lighting and the wind for ventilation.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Together, these strategies create high performance buildings that work with nature rather than against.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Naval architecture, also known as naval engineering, is an engineering discipline dealing with the engineering design process, shipbuilding, maintenance, and operation of marine vessels and structures.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Naval architecture involves basic and applied research, design, development, design evaluation, and calculations during all stages of the life of a marine vehicle.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Preliminary design of the vessel, its detailed design, construction, trials, operation and maintenance, launching, and dry-docking are the main activities involved.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Ship design calculations are also required for ships being modified (by means of conversion, rebuilding, modernization, or repair).
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] Naval architecture also involves the formulation of safety regulations and damage control rules and the approval and certification of ship designs to meet statutory and non-statutory requirements.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] "Architecture" is used as a metaphor for many modern techniques or fields for structuring abstractions.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] The term 'seismic architecture' or 'earthquake architecture' was first introduced in 1985 by Robert Reitherman.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] The phrase "earthquake architecture" is used to describe a degree of architectural expression of earthquake resistance or implication of architectural configuration, form, or style in earthquake resistance.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] It is also used to describe buildings in which seismic design considerations impacted its architecture.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] It may be considered a new aesthetic approach in designing structures in seismic prone areas.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] The wide breadth of expressive possibilities ranges from metaphorical uses of seismic issues to the more straightforward exposure of seismic technology.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/architecture] While outcomes of an earthquake architecture can be very diverse in their physical manifestations, architectural expression of seismic principles can also take many forms and levels of sophistication.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/asbestos-testing-and-consultancy-association] The **Asbestos Testing And Consultancy Association** (**ATAC**) is a British trade association for companies in the United Kingdom who carry out asbestos surveying, analytical and laboratory work.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/asbestos-testing-and-consultancy-association] The organisation was founded in Burton-on-Trent in 1990.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/asbestos-testing-and-consultancy-association] It was founded by various consultancy companies through its sister association, the Asbestos Removal Contractors Association (ARCA), as the consultancies required a trade association voice of their own.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/asbestos-testing-and-consultancy-association] The head office is in Burton and there is a training centre in Rayleigh, Essex, the association also has access to various other training centres across the UK.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/asbestos-testing-and-consultancy-association] The association was up until 2013 run on a day-to-day basis by Ian Stone CCP who has been in the asbestos industry for over fifteen years.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/asbestos-testing-and-consultancy-association] Ian has worked on both the asbestos consultancy and asbestos removal sides of the industry.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/asbestos-testing-and-consultancy-association] The current Chairman of ATAC is Andrew Jackson who has been in the industry for nearly two decades, he also is the managing director of an asbestos and statutory compliance consultancy (Acorn Analytical Services Ltd).
[src:national-fire-protection-association/asbestos-testing-and-consultancy-association] Andrew replaced Jonathan Francis as ATAC Chairman in 2011 and will hold the tenure for two years.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/asbestos-testing-and-consultancy-association] Ian Stone has since left ATAC after 3 years at the association.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/asbestos-testing-and-consultancy-association] During Ian's time at the association he helped create various industry recognised qualifications which helped place ATAC at the forefront of the asbestos industry.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/asbestos-testing-and-consultancy-association] He is now a Director of Acorn Analytical Services.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/asbestos-testing-and-consultancy-association] He works from the Northampton and London offices providing consultancy to various large scale and blue chip clients.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/asbestos-testing-and-consultancy-association] ATAC is at the forefront of the asbestos industry raising awareness about asbestos issues.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/asbestos-testing-and-consultancy-association] They participated in a campaign in 2010 about Asbestos In Schools, which led the association to be part of a parliamentary steering group.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/asbestos-testing-and-consultancy-association] The association also works alongside the Health and Safety Executive (HSE) and other regulatory bodies such as the United Kingdom Accreditation Service (UKAS) to help raise awareness of asbestos and to improve the standards within the asbestos industry.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/asbestos-testing-and-consultancy-association] The association has 70 member companies which are located across the UK, there are also information members of the association who subscribe from Europe and internationally.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/national-fire-protection-association] The **National Fire Protection Association** (**NFPA**) is a U.S.-based international nonprofit organization devoted to eliminating death, injury, property damage, and economic loss due to fire, electrical, and related hazards.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/national-fire-protection-association] As of 2025, the NFPA claims to have 50,000 members and 10,000 volunteers working with the organization through its 250 technical committees.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/national-fire-protection-association] In 1895, a Committee on Automatic Sprinkler Protection was formed in Massachusetts by men affiliated with several fire insurance companies and a pipe manufacturer to develop a uniform standard for the design and installation of fire sprinkler systems.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/national-fire-protection-association] At the time, there were nine such standards in effect within 100 miles (160 km) of Boston, Massachusetts, and such diversity was causing great difficulties for plumbers working in the New England region.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/national-fire-protection-association] The next year, the committee published its initial report on a uniform standard and later formed the NFPA in late 1896.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/national-fire-protection-association] The committee's initial report evolved into NFPA 13, *Standard for the Installation of Sprinkler Systems,* the most widely used fire sprinkler standard.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/national-fire-protection-association] Around 1904, the NFPA began expanding its membership from affiliates of fire insurance companies to many other organizations and individuals, and also broadened its mission beyond promulgating fire sprinkler standards.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/national-fire-protection-association] The association publishes more than 300 consensus codes and standards intended to minimize the possibility and effects of fire and other risks.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/national-fire-protection-association] The codes and standards are administered by more than 250 technical committees consisting of approximately 9,000 volunteers.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/national-fire-protection-association] A children's book about Sparky by Don Hoffman was published in 2011.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/national-fire-protection-association] He serves as the spokesdog for Fire Prevention Week each October in the United States and Canada.
[src:national-fire-protection-association/national-fire-protection-association] NFPA sponsored a NASCAR O'Reilly Auto Parts Series race at the Martinsville Speedway on March 28, 2026, called the NFPA 250.
